"Fraanje P.J.","Cascading of renewable resources hemp and reed",1997,"Industrial Crops and Products","6","3-4",,"201","212",,,10.1016/S0926-6690(97)00009-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030802216&partnerID=40&md5=9c96c12c8f7ca1142f24da344fae6bd5","IVAM Environmental Research, University of Amsterdam, P.O. Box 18 180, 1001 ZB Amsterdam, Netherlands","Fraanje, P.J., IVAM Environmental Research, University of Amsterdam, P.O. Box 18 180, 1001 ZB Amsterdam, Netherlands","Resource-cascading, the sequential exploitation of the full potential of a resource during its use, is one of the ways to improve efficiency of raw materials use. To design a good cascade knowledge of the typical properties and structures of the plant is useful. In this article it is shown that cascading of the renewable resources hemp and reed can lead to large savings in primary resource use. Resource cascading can therefore make the option to replace non-renewable resources by renewables more realistic. In comparison with using biomass (e.g. reed, hemp, straw) for energy directly, cascading also means that, carbondioxide emission, is postponed. This is interesting in relation to global warming.","Hemp Cascading; Reed; Renewable resources","emissions control; hemp resources; reed resources; renewable resources; resources cascading; Cannabis; Cannabis sativa; Phragmites",,,,,,"Backe, H., (1936) Der Hanfanbau, , Parey Verlag, Berlin; Von Berswordt-Wallrabe, Th., (1995) Riet Voor Dakbedekking, , LUW vakgroep Agronomie, Wageningen; Daly, H., Towards some operational principles of sustainable development (1990) Ecol. Econ., 2 (1), pp. 1-6; Diels, L., (1918) Ersatzstoffe aus dem Pflanzenreich, , Stuttgart; Fraanje, P.J., Lafleur, M.C.C., Sustainable use of wood in the Netherlands (1994) IVAM Environmental Research, 94 (8). , University of Amsterdam; Fraanje, P.J., Fibre-hemp as a building material (1995) IVAM Environmental Research, 95 (6). , University of Amsterdam; Goulding, E., (191